NGS Discriminant Gender Analysis for Full Data

Diane Park

9 October 2018

Introduction

Discriminant analysis (DA) is used to predict the probability of belonging to a given class based on one or multiple predictor variables. In this research, the classes for gender are Femal (0) and Male (1). We consider three different types of DAs: Linear discriminant analysis (LDA), quadratic discriminant analysis (QDA) and Regularized discriminant anlysis (RDA).

  • Linear discriminant analysis (LDA): Uses linear combinations of predictors to predict the class of a given observation. Assumes that the predictor variables are normally distributed and the classes have identical variances.

  • Quadratic discriminant analysis (QDA): Assumes that the predictor variables are normally distributed, but there is no assumption that the covariance matrix of classes is the same.

  • Regularized discriminant anlysis (RDA): generalise LDA and QDA using parameter and .
